Document: Reflection Probes
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/global_illumination/reflection_probes.rst
Summary: This section explains the purpose and usage of ReflectionProbe nodes in Godot Engine for providing accurate reflections and ambient light.
Reflection probes are used as a source of reflected and ambient light for objects within their area of influence. They can provide more accurate reflections than VoxelGI and SDFGI while being relatively inexpensive in terms of system resources. Reflection probes can also store ambient light, serving as a lower-end alternative to VoxelGI and SDFGI when baked lightmaps are not feasible, such as in procedurally generated levels. They can be used concurrently with screen-space reflections to offer reflections for off-screen objects, with Godot blending the two techniques.

See also: For a comparison of global illumination techniques in Godot 4, refer to the introduction to global illumination comparison.
---CHUNK---
Document: Reflection Probes
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/global_illumination/reflection_probes.rst
Summary: This section visually compares the effects of ReflectionProbe nodes with and without screen-space reflections, demonstrating their combined benefits.

The first image shows a scene where a ReflectionProbe is disabled, and the environment sky is used as a fallback for reflections. The second image shows the same scene with a ReflectionProbe enabled, providing more accurate reflections of the scene's geometry. The third image illustrates a scenario where both a ReflectionProbe and LightmapGI are used simultaneously, showing that the lightmap's indirect lighting appears within the reflection.

Combining ReflectionProbe nodes with screen-space reflections (SSR) offers a powerful way to achieve high-quality reflections. Reflection probes provide stable, general reflections of the room's structure, which persist even for objects that are off-screen. Screen-space reflections, on the other hand, excel at capturing real-time, detailed reflections of small objects and dynamic elements that are currently visible on screen.

The fourth image displays reflections in a room using only a ReflectionProbe. It highlights a limitation: small details within the scene do not have corresponding reflections because the probe captures a broader, less detailed view.

The fifth image demonstrates reflections using only screen-space reflections. This image points out a drawback of SSR: reflections on the sides of the room's walls are partially missing because they fall outside the screen's view.

The final image showcases the combined effect of using both a ReflectionProbe and screen-space reflections. In this setup, SSR reflections are blended with the ReflectionProbe's reflections. This blend acts as a fallback mechanism; when the ReflectionProbe might not provide a suitable reflection (e.g., for dynamic objects or specific angles), SSR can fill in the gaps with real-time, on-screen details, resulting in a more complete and visually appealing reflection system.
