Document: Reflection Probes
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/global_illumination/reflection_probes.rst
Summary: This section explains how to set up and configure ReflectionProbe nodes in a Godot 3D scene for global illumination.
To set up a ReflectionProbe, add a ReflectionProbe node to your scene. Configure the ReflectionProbe's extents in the inspector to fit your scene. For reasonably accurate reflections, generally use one ReflectionProbe node per room, or more for very large rooms. Tip: ReflectionProbe extents are not restricted to being square, and the ReflectionProbe node can be rotated to fit rooms not aligned with the X/Z grid. This allows for better room coverage without needing to place excessive ReflectionProbe nodes.
---CHUNK---
Document: ReflectionProbe properties
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/global_illumination/reflection_probes.rst
Summary: This section details the properties of the ReflectionProbe node in Godot Engine, covering update modes, visual appearance, and ambient lighting settings.

- **Update Mode:** Controls when the reflection probe updates.
  - **Once:** Renders the scene once every time the ReflectionProbe is moved. This is faster than **Always**.
  - **Always:** Forces the probe to re-render everything around it every frame.
  Key Rule: Leave this property on **Once** (default) unless you need the reflection probe to update every frame.
- **Intensity:** The brightness of the reflections and ambient lighting. Default is 1.0. Can be decreased if reflections appear too strong.
- **Max Distance:** Controls the maximum distance used by the ReflectionProbe's internal camera. The distance is always at least equal to the **Extents**, but this can be increased to make objects located outside the extents visible in reflections. This property does not affect the maximum distance at which the ReflectionProbe itself is visible.
- **Extents:** The area that will be affected by the ReflectionProbe's lighting and reflections.
- **Origin Offset:** The origin to use for the internal camera used for reflection probe rendering. This must always be constrained within the **Extents**. Adjust this to prevent the reflection from being obstructed by a solid object located exactly at the center of the ReflectionProbe.
- **Box Projection:** Controls whether parallax correction is used when rendering the reflection probe. This adjusts the reflection's appearance depending on the camera's position relative to the reflection probe. This has a small performance cost but can significantly improve quality in box-shaped rooms. It is less effective in irregularly shaped rooms.
- **Interior:** If enabled, ambient lighting will not be sourced from the environment sky, and the background sky won't be rendered onto the reflection probe.
- **Enable Shadows:** Controls whether real-time light shadows are rendered within the reflection probe. Enabling this improves reflection quality at the cost of performance.
  Key Rule: This should be left disabled for reflection probes with the **Always** update mode, as it's very expensive to render reflections with shadows every frame. Fully baked light shadows are not affected by this setting and will be rendered in the reflection probe regardless.
- **Cull Mask:** Controls which objects are visible in the reflection. Can be used to improve performance by excluding small objects or to prevent an object from having self-reflection artifacts when **Origin Offset** cannot be used.
- **Mesh LOD Threshold:** The automatic level of detail threshold for rendering meshes within the reflection. This only affects meshes with automatically generated LODs. Higher values can improve performance by using less detailed geometry, especially for distant objects.

The Ambient category features several properties to adjust ambient lighting rendered by the ReflectionProbe:

- **Mode:**
  - **Disabled:** No ambient light is added by the probe.
  - **Environment:** Ambient light color is sampled from the environment sky (if **Interior** is disabled) and the reflection's average color.
  - **Constant Color:** The color specified in the **Color** property is used. This mode can approximate area lighting.
- **Color:** The color to use when the ambient light mode is set to **Constant Color**.
- **Color Energy:** The multiplier for the ambient light custom **Color**. This only has an effect when the ambient light mode is **Constant Color**.
---CHUNK---
Document: ReflectionProbe blending
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/global_illumination/reflection_probes.rst
Summary: Explains how ReflectionProbes blend with each other and with global illumination techniques for smoother reflections.
ReflectionProbe blending
To make transitions between reflection sources smoother, Godot supports automatic probe blending. Up to 4 ReflectionProbes can be blended together at a given location. A ReflectionProbe will also fade out smoothly back to environment lighting when it isn't touching any other ReflectionProbe node. SDFGI and VoxelGI will blend in smoothly with ReflectionProbes if used. This allows placing ReflectionProbes strategically to get more accurate (or fully real-time) reflections where needed, while still having rough reflections available in the VoxelGI or SDFGI's area of influence. To make several ReflectionProbes blend with each other, you need to have part of each ReflectionProbe overlap each other's area. The extents should only overlap as little as possible with other reflection probes to improve rendering performance (typically a few units in 3D space).
---CHUNK---
Document: Reflection Probes
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/global_illumination/reflection_probes.rst
Summary: This section details the limitations of reflection probes in different Godot renderers.
When using the Forward+ renderer, Godot uses a clustering approach for reflection probe rendering. While many reflection probes can be added, there's a default limit of 512 clustered elements in the current camera view. A clustered element can be an omni light, a spot light, a decal, or a reflection probe. This limit can be increased in Project Settings under Rendering > Limits > Cluster Builder by adjusting Max Clustered Elements.

When using the Mobile renderer, only 8 reflection probes can be applied to each individual Mesh resource. If more reflection probes affect a single mesh, not all of them will be rendered on that mesh.

Similarly, when using the Compatibility renderer, up to 2 reflection probes can be applied per mesh. If more than 2 reflection probes affect a single mesh, additional probes will not be rendered.